2 Linear Regression

Description of the work for this week

The data is based on an International survey of Approaches to Learning. It was gathered in 2014-2015 in Finland by Kimmo Vehkalahti I have prepared a subdataset to for this analysis. It consists of 166 respondent and 7 variables. Background variables include age and gender of the students. Measures include Points (overall), Attitude (towards statistics) and three measures of learning styles: Deep, Strategic and Surface. see more

3 Linear regression

The dependent variable was Points. In the first model, the explanatory variables were Attitude, stra and deep. According to the results, only Attitude had significant relationship with the target variable. Thus, I made a new, simple linear regression model with only Attitude as an explanatory variable. The summaries of both models below.

Interpretation of the statistical test:

  • p-value for the model is less than .001 so the model is statistically significant.
  • p-value for Attitude is less than .001 so its relationship with the target variable is statistically significant.
model_1 <- lm(Points ~ Attitude + stra + deep, data = lr14)
summary(model_1)

4 Model interpretation

Multiple R-squared in simple linear regression is just the square of the correlation coefficient between the two variables, 0.19. This means that 19% of the variance in points is explained by Attitude. The Estimate for Attitude means that when Points increase with 1, Attitude increases approximately 0.35. There is a positive linear relationship, as can be seen also in the plot below.

qplot(Points, Attitude, data = lr14) + geom_smooth(method = "lm")

5 Model diagnostics

Is the model in line with the assumptions of linear regression? This is explored with the three plots below.

1 Are the residuals normally distributed? From the QQ-plot we can see that there is a reasonable fit with the normality assumption.

2 Do the errors have constant variance? In other words, the variance should not depend on the explanatory variable. Residuals vs Fitted -plot shows, that the variance does not increase when the fitted values increase.

3 Is there too high of an impact with certain observations? From Residuals vs.Leverage -plot we can see, that the highest leverage being less than .05 we dont have to worry that simple observations have too much power in the model.

# Model diagnostics
# Using par-fuction to place following 4 graphs to the same plot
par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(model_2, which = c(1,2,5))

This survey data is from secondary education of two Portuguese schools. It includes x variables about student achievement, alcoholc consumption etc. Data source and more information here: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Student+Performance

In this analysis, I will take four variables and look at their relationship to alcohol consumption. The exlanatory variable are: age, gender, address and absences. Build Logistic regression

# build the model
m <- glm(data=alcs, high_use ~ sex + address + absences + age, family="binomial")
summary(m)

Interpretation: The estimate for the inercept is -4.00961, that is to log odds of being a high alcohol user and female, urban address, zero absences and youngest in the sample. From log odds we can calculate the odds by exponenting the estimate, that is -16. The other estimates tell us how much the log odds change if the explanatory variable changes. For example, if the absences (continous variable) increase by 1, the log odds increase .09283. As sex is a dichotomous variable, that coefficient 0.98222 is a log odds ratio between the female and the male group.

Z-value is a results of a statistical test which tells whether the variables power is statistically significant in the model (if z is >2 or <-2). p-value tells quite the same. We can see, that sex and absences are statistically significant predictors.

# build a new model with only significant predictors
m2 <- glm(data=alcs, high_use ~ sex + absences, family="binomial")

# calculate odd ratios by exponenting the coefficients of the model 
OR <- coef(m2) %>% exp
# and the same for confidence intervals
CI <- confint(m2) %>% exp
## Waiting for profiling to be done...
# print them out
cbind(OR, CI)
##                   OR     2.5 %    97.5 %
## (Intercept) 0.159445 0.1012577 0.2427684
## sexM        2.658116 1.6710354 4.2863129
## absences    1.101409 1.0549317 1.1548057

According to the odds ratio, males are 2.6 times more likely to be high users of alcohol. For every absence, the probability that the student is a heavy drinker is 1.1 times more likely.

Explore the predictive power

# Use prdeict() to compute probabilites based on the logit model. 
# type maked the probalities be probalities instead of log of odds, the default
probabilities <- predict(m2, type="response")
# add the probs in the data frame
alcs <- mutate (alcs, probs = probabilities)
# use the probs to make a prediction of high use
# threshold will be set to .5. If we want less false positives, we should increase the threshold
alcs <- mutate(alcs, prediction = probs > .5)
# crosstabs the target versus predictions
table(high_use = alcs$high_use, prediction = alcs$prediction)
##         prediction
## high_use FALSE TRUE
##    FALSE   258   10
##    TRUE     88   26
# plot
ggplot(alcs, aes(x = probs, y = high_use, col = prediction)) + geom_point()

The confusion matrix shows, that there are quite a lot of false positives (n=31) and false negatives (n=73)

loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}
# call the function to compute the average of wrong predictions
loss_func(class = alcs$high_use, prob = alcs$prediction)
## [1] 0.2565445

The loss function calculates the average n. of wrong predictions, that is the training error. In this case the prediction is wrong in 27,2% cases. Its still better than flipping a coin.

# 10-fold cross-validation for the model
library(boot)
cv <- cv.glm(data = alcs, cost = loss_func, glmfit = m, K = 10)
# cv.glm computes the error and stores it in delta, print delta
cv$delta[1]
## [1] 0.2513089

Accoring to 10-fold cross-validation, average number of wrong predictions is 0.25. Thus, my model is a bit better than the one in DataCamp (error .26). Wohoo!

.

4 Clustering and classification

Today we are first building a Linear Discriminant Model and testing its predictive power. Last week we used logistic regression to predict two categories (true/false). When we have more two, we can use LDA. It focuses on maximizing the separability among known categories. It is a supervized classification method, in contrast to K-means clustering, which is an unsupervized method. We will try that in the end of this exercise.

Results show the group-specific means for each covariate, for which the LDA tries to maximize the difference between groups.

Proportion of trace tells the between between-group variance. Thus, LD1 explains 96% of the between-group variance.

# draw the LDA(bi) plot
# the function for lda biplot arrows
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

# target classes as numeric
classes <- as.numeric(train$crime)

# plot the lda results
plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2, col = classes, pch = classes)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 1)

We can see, that the category high is best separated. From the numeric results we saw, that LD1 (x-axis) explained 95% of the between-group variance.

Predict the classes with the LDA model

K-means clustering

km <- kmeans(boston_sc, centers = 4)

Well that was simple. Lets see what is the best number of clusters with a qplot.

# K-means might produce different results every time, because it randomly assigns the initial cluster centers. The function set.seed() can be used to deal with that.
set.seed(123)
# set the max number of clusters
k_max <- 10
# count the WCSS = within cluster sum of squares and plot it
twcss <- sapply(1:k_max, function(k){kmeans(boston_sc, k)$tot.withinss})
qplot(x = 1:k_max, y = twcss, geom = 'line')

WCSS is one method to find the optimal number off clusters. It tells how close the observations are to the cluster center. The optimal number of clusters is when the total WCSS drops radically. Based on the plot, the optimum number of clusters should be 2 (see x-axis). So lets run the clustering again with 2 centroids.

Visualize the clusters

boston_sc <- as.data.frame(boston_sc)
# run kmeans again with 2 centroids
km <- kmeans(boston_sc, centers = 2)
# visualize the clusters
pairs(boston_sc[5:8], col = km$cluster)

So the data is divided to two clusters and the plotted with pairs. From the plot we can see for example, that the houses in the 1st cluster (in red) have - lower AGE and lower NOX (nitrogen oxides concentration) - more rooms (RM, average number of rooms per dwelling), and higher distance to employment centers (DIS)

The non-standardized plot is not much helpful, because variables power is related to their scale. For example, the mean of gni is 17600, whereas other variables has mean value less than 100, some of them less than 1. This explains the long length of the gni arrow in the plot.

Standardized data: Like we saw from the correlation plot, maternal mortality and adolescent birth rate are highly related. In the biplot, if the arrows are close to one another, variables have high correlation.

The first principal component (PC1) simplifies the picture as follows: There is a continuum, where in another end there are countries with high maternal mortality and adolescent birth rate, and in the opposite end high life expectancy, more years in education, and better F/M ratio in secondary education.

The plot shows how the countries (rows) align with dimensions. For example, there are countries with have high maternal mortality and adolescene birth rate, but still score high is gender equality regarding labour and politics (PC2). The index number of these countries are seen in the upper left corner of the plot.

Interpretation of components

The first principal component (PC1) reflects the overall health and gender equality in the private sphere.

The second principal component (PC2) reflects gender equality in the public sphere. The higher the value of PC2, the higher the F/M ratio in labour and women representatives in parliament.

Eigenvalues: First dimension explains 16.0, second 13.3 percent of the variance of the variables in the model. Individuals: rows in the data, showing first 10. If an individual is well projected in the dimension, the cos2 is close to 1 eta2: If the value is close to 1, there is a strong link between the variable and the dimension. In dim1, strongest variables are tea.time and dinner, in Dim2, Tea and Home.

Supplementary variables do not contribute to the dimensions (not included in the model), but correspondingly we can see how they are linked to dimensions.

par (mfrow = c(2,2))
plot.MCA(mca, invisible=c("var","quali.sup"), cex=0.7, title="Individuals")

plot.MCA(mca, invisible=c("ind","quali.sup"), cex=0.7, title="Variables")

plot.MCA(mca, invisible=c("ind", "var"), cex=0.7, title="Supplementary variables")

plot.MCA(mca, invisible=c("quali.sup"), cex=0.7, habillage = "quali", title="Variables and individuals")

# habillage = "quali" means one color is used for each categorical variables;

It is possible to plot the individuals and variables in different and in the same plot. From the plot we can see which variables define the dimensions. Distance from the origo represents power.

# SelectMod="contrib 8" displays 8 variables with highest contribution to the dimensions
# select = "contrib 3" shows the labels of 3 individuals that contribute the most to the dimensions
plot.MCA(mca, invisible=c("quali.sup"), selectMod="contrib 8", select = "contrib 3", cex=0.7, title="Variables and individuals")

Here we can see the variables and individuals together. Only those with most contribution have labels to make the plot more readable.

plot.MCA(mca, choix="var", xlim=c(0,0.5), ylim=c(0,0.5))

This choix-version of the MCA-plot shows the links between variables and dimensions. The value (for the categorical variables) is the squared correlation ratio between the dimension and the variable. So bigger value means stronger link with the dimension.

plot.MCA(mca, invisible=c("quali.sup", "var"), select = "contrib 10", habillage = "Tea", cex=0.7, title="Individuals grouped by Tea type")

And finally, a grouped plot: based on Tea type, there seems to be quite clear clusters in the data. Green tea score high on Dim1 and mid on Dim2. Thats understandable, as strongest variables in Dim1 where teatime and dinner. And in Dim2, breakfast and home - so Earl Grey it is.
